occurrences.line_text: Which was the conquest of the gentlest Knight,
But he himselfe, which did that conquest make;
So led this Knight his captyue with like conquest wonne.
Was neuer man, who most conquestes atchieu'd
That hath so many haughtie conquests wonne?
In meed of these great conquests by them got,
That shall their conquests through all lands extend,
And all the conquests, which them high did reare,
His famous conquests highly magnifide:
With his faire paragon, his conquests part,
And in his conscience made a secret breach,
Whiles trembling horror did his conscience dant,
In that disease of grieued conscience,
Who ioyous of his cured conscience,
My conscience cleare with guilty bands would bind?
Albe her guiltlesse conscience her cleard,
According to the line of conscience,
And sorrowes feeling, yet with conscience
The fields, the floods, the heauens with one consent
They soone consent: so forth with her they fare,
To beene with Guyon knit in one consent,
Accord of friends, consent of parents sought,
Till by consent of Commons and of Peares,
And all her sister Nymphes with one consent
A lay of loues delight, with sweet consent:
They by consent should chose the stoutest three,
To which folke-mote they all with one consent,
Then all with one consent did yeeld the prize
And many othes, she yeelded her consent
Did closely with a cruell one consent,
For lodging there without her owne consent:
Resolu'd with him to wend, gainst all her friends consent.
Consent, that I who stood all fearelesse free,
Who thereto did with readie will consent,
Of louers lincked in true harts consent;
But he thereto would by no meanes consent;
Which might concluded be by mutuall consent.
Then when she wakt, they all gaue one consent,
Were by them slaine by generall consent;
And to my foe hath guilefully consented:
Consisted much in that aduentures priefe.
To him assembled with one full consort,
And made emongst them selues a sweet consort,
On thother side in one consort there sate,
Some song in sweet consort, some laught for ioy,
That wonder was to heare their trim consort.
The Lyon there did with the Lambe consort,
But Coridon durst not with him consort,
So forth they pas, a well consorted paire,
In which being consorted with Manild,
Was there consorted in one harmonee,
Where they in secret counsell close conspird,
Against that Castles Lord they gan conspire,
But Fortune did not with his will conspire.
So both conspiring, gan to intimate
Therefore conspiring all together plaine,
And warning giue, that enemies conspyre,
Remember) had her counsels false conspyred,
With constancy and care, gainst daunger and dismay.
Her constant hart did tempt with diuerse guile:
And euermore in constant carefull mind
But that with constant zeale, and courage bold,
Ne diuelish thoughts dismay thy constant spright.
But she no whit did chaunge her constant mood:
So did she all, that might his constant hart
But constant keepe the way, in which ye stand;
In constant peace their kingdomes did containe,
The constant paire heard all, that he did say,
The whiles faire Britomart, whose constant mind,
And guide the heauenly causes to their constant terme.
Her constant mind could moue at all he saw,
But Artegall with constant firme intent,
Her constant mynd could not a whit remoue,
Of whom he did great Constantine beget,
They crownd the second Constantine with ioyous teares,
By this the sonnes of Constantine, which fled,
Constantius, a man of mickle might,
Of his coosin Constantius without dread
And so doe make contrarie constitution
That euery wight to shrowd it did constrain,
The God, though loth, yet was constraind t'obay,
As if some pensiue thought co[n]straind her gentle spright.
In which him vanquisht she to fly constraind:
The same to loue he strongly was constraind:
Till he with old Latinus was constraind,
That soone to loose her wicked bands did her constraine.
And them constraine in equall teme to draw.
But such, as want of harbour did constraine:
Till struggling strong did him at last constraine,
Whom rauenous hunger did thereto constraine:
Whenas no strength, nor stroks mote him constraine
Till ruth and fraile affection did constraine,
And hundred knots that did him sore constraine:
Yet now my lucklesse lot doth me constraine
Yet her for to awake he did the more constraine.
But yet by torture he would her constraine
Her forward still with torture did constraine,
My softened heart so sorely doth constraine,
Or loue of fairest Ladie could constraine.
Feare of her safety did her not constraine,
Her forth to fetch, and Proteus to constraine:
But he for nought could him thereto constraine.
Annoy this noble Knight, and sorely him constraine.
To peace, then needlesse trouble to constraine.
That it to such a streight mote you constraine)
When as necessitie doth it constraine.
Toward the Castle, where if need constraine,
Whom he likewise right sorely did constraine,
That for his safety he did him constraine
That workes it to his will, then he that it constraines.
When too huge toile and labour them constraines:
His Lady sad to see his sore constraint,
Loue of your selfe, she said, and deare constraint
And sad to see her sorrowfull constraint
As when her face is staynd with magicke arts constraint.
Through long enprisonment, and hard constraint,
Whom late I left in langourous constraint?
She set her downe to weepe for sore constraint,
Strooke him so hugely, that through great constraint
Sith brought she was now to so hard constraint,
For nothing may impresse so deare constraint,
The cause of that his sorrowfull constraint;
Till strong constraint did her thereto enforce.
That to the ground he is perforce constraynd
Amongst the rest some one through loues constrayning,
And her sad selfe with carefull hand constrayning
That much she muz'd, yet could not construe it
Were cleane consum'd, and all his vitall powres
In one sad night consumd, and throwen downe:
Consum'd, but did him selfe to safetie retyre.
That all his substance was consum'd to nought,
Harrow, the flames, which me consume (said hee)
Consume, till all their warlike puissaunce be spent.
Doth it consume, and into nothing go,
Consume his hart, and scorch his Idoles face,
And did consume his gall with anguish sore,
That doth with curelesse care consume the hart,
And also nigh consumed is the lingring day.
Consumed had their goods, and thriftlesse howres,
Such earthly mettals soone consumed bene:
After lost credite and consumed thrift,
And quenched quite, like a consumed torch,
Through wilfull penury consumed quight,
That rots the marrow, and consumes the braine:
Of euery thing consumes, and calcineth by art.
Himselfe to chearish, and consuming thought
Fraile Ladies hart with loues consuming rage,
That he might taste the sweet consuming woe,
In wilfull languor and consuming smart,
And euermore encreased her consuming paine.
Consuming Riotise, and guilty Dread
And nourisheth her owne consuming smart?
That through the great contagion direfull deadly stunck.
The fell contagion may thereof restraine,
In which a puddle of contagion was,
Contagious poyson close through euery vaine,
My narrow leaues cannot in them containe
No song but did containe a louely dit:
In constant peace their kingdomes did containe,
That but the fruit more sweetnesse did containe,
That seem'd the Ocean could not containe them there.
May her perhaps containe, that else would algates fleet.
Ne in small meares containe his glory great,
That glorious belt did in it selfe containe,
Tormented sore, could not containe it still,
And all that did within them all containe;
Al which the heauens containe, & in their courses guide.
Ne feed on ought, the which doth bloud containe,
Ne within reasons rule, her madding mood containe.
As to abandon, that which doth containe
Nor lawes of men, that common weales containe,
From that they most affect, and in due termes containe.
With open mouth, that seemed to containe
By her the heauen is in his course contained,
Great threasure sithence we did finde contained;
Therewith containes his heauenly Common-weale,
What euer thing was in the world contaynd,
Contayned be, and in small compasse hild?
In whose right hands great power is contayned,
Which in an other Canto will be best contayned.
To stirre vp strife, and troublous contecke broch:
But both his challenge and him selfe contemned,
For contemplation sake: yet otherwise,
His name was heauenly Contemplation;
In contemplation of diuinitie:
And his contempt, that did her iudg'ment breake.
Now base and contemptible did appeare,
His foes haue slaine themselues, with whom he should contend.
Which greater grew, the more she did contend,
As hagard hauke presuming to contend
Yet well he wist, that who so would contend
Whiles they are weake betimes with them contend:
That ioyes for crownes and kingdomes to contend;
Out of his swowne arose, fresh to contend,
Which therein bathing, seemed to contend,
To loose his shield, and long while did contend:
And both the parts did speake, and both contended;
Departed thence with full contended mynd;
To deeme this doutfull case, for which they all co[n]tended.
Yet he at last contending to excell
For this same night. The knight was well content:
Not all content, yet seemd she to appease
Did her content to please their feeble eyes,
In full content he there did long enioy,
Who not content so fowly to deuoure
Yet cruell Cupid, not herewith content,
Content to heare him speake, and glad to rest withall.
So as she to his speeches was content
Their spotlesse pleasures, and sweet loues content.
Giue her great comfort, and some harts content.
Yet not content, more to increase his shame,
Faire was the Ladie sure, that mote content
Some place of succour to content his mynd,
But doe my self, with that I haue, content;
Both of his speach that wrought him great content,
With which the Knight him selfe did much content,
Fit to keepe sheepe, vnfit for loues content:
Would not so rest contented with his right,
The which doth litle craue contented to abyde.
To sad decay, that might contented liue.
But fittest is, that all contented rest
Contented, greater mischiefe on her threw,
Their fell contention still increased more,
Whom all that folke with such contention,
Coles of contention and whot vengeance tynd.
Great Godmer threw, in fierce contention,
When as their sharpe contention he had ceased,
With bitter rage and fell contention,
Did striue to match with strong contention,
Then fowle reuenging rage, and base contentious iarre.
Some troublous vprore or contentious fray,
When not for malice and contentious crimes,
Tumultuous trouble and contentious iarre,
Which stirs vp anguish and contentious rage:
Of warres delight, and worlds contentious toyle,
The noblest mind the best contentment has.
Gaue wondrous great contentment to the knight,
That were too long their infinite contents
A harder lesson, to learne Continence
And continence of life, that all forgon,
That raignest also in the Continent,
She threw her selfe downe on the Continent,
But th'head fell backeward on the continent.
Vnlesse that she were continent and chast,
Or faultie thoughts continewd, as was fit;
And there all day continew'd cruell fight,
And all that night her course continewed:
Her loue is firme, her care continuall,
And with continuall watch did warely keepe;
And yet his peace is but continuall iarre:
That through continuall practise and vsage,
And wearie waxe of his continuall stay.
There those fiue sisters had continuall trade,
The world in his continuall course to keepe,
There is continuall spring, and haruest there
Continuall, both meeting at one time:
Suspect her truth, and keepe continuall spy
But that continuall battery will riue,
In drery darkenesse, and continuall feare
Out of her thraldome and continuall feare?
Continuall siege vnto her gentle hart;
Whom when the watch, that kept continuall ward
What though the sea with waues continuall
But with continuall candlelight, which delt
And kept them with continuall watch and ward,
A shaking feuer raignd continually:
And hungry Wolues continually did howle,
And Gehons golden waues doe wash continually.
To God for vengeance cryde continually,
Plonged continually of cruell Sprights,
Continually, and cooling breath inspyre.
Therein gaue light, and flam'd continually:
Infinit streames continually did well
And causelesse crimes continually to frame,
His eye-lids sad, but watcht continually,
And some of Beares, that groynd continually,
As that, through long continuance of his course,
As he had vow'd, some small continuaunce
And afterwards continu'd there a while,
But still continu'd his assault the more,
Thus there long while continu'd Artegall,
There she continu'd for a certaine space,
Continu'd still his course, and by the way
During all which, those knights continu'd there,
Thus Calidore continu'd there long time,
Thus long continu'd Claribell a thrall,
And daunger well he wist long to continue there.
Yet so, as bound to me he may continue still.
His kingdome would continue but a while.
Or at more ease continue there his thrall:
And the old cause of my continued paine
Against that same fift bulwarke they continued fight.
Long while they then continued in that wize,
So he continued all that day throughout,
There he continued in this carefull plight,
Companion she became, and so continued long.
Thus they long while continued in fight,
To contract wedlock: (so the fates ordaind.)
Wedlock contract in bloud, and eke in blood
To be contrarie to the worke, which ye intend.
Of filthy lust, contrarie vnto kind:
She turned her contrarie to the Sunne,
With squinted eyes contrarie wayes intended,
The other backe retired, and contrarie trode.
Forcibly driuen with contrarie tydes
Flowes vp the Shenan with contrarie forse,
But whosoeuer contrarie doth proue,
Though of contrarie natures each to other:
And so doe make contrarie constitution
But then for her, on the contrarie part,
But the wyld man, contrarie to her feare,
There did they find, contrarie to their thought,
But this coy Damzell thought contrariwize,
Meetes two contrary billowes by the way,
And quite contrary to her sisters kind;
And his contrary obiect most deface,
But this same was to that quite contrary,
All ignoraunt of her contrary sex,
Thrise she her turnd contrary, and returnd,
All contrary, for she the right did shunne,
From one to other so quite contrary:
There was I found, contrary to my thought,
That with the wind, contrary courses sew,
But euermore contrary hath bene tryde,
Yet rather counseld him contrarywize,
Betrayd his contrey vnto forreine spoyle:
I put the teares of my contrition,
Three ages, such as mortall men contriue,
For other none such passion can contriue
The controuerse of beauties soueraine grace;
Was afterward, I know not how, conuaid
Was close conuaid, and to the back-gate brought,
He is conuaide, but how or where, here fits not tell.
Into their names the title to conuart,
And her to Faerie court safe to conuay,
From powrefull eyes close venim doth conuay
But if that Dwarfe I could with me conuay,
Should as his purchast prize with him conuay
Conuay to be recur'd. She thankt him deare,
How thence she might conuay him to some place.
Or from the Goat her kidde how to conuay;
Vnto their dwelling did them close conuay.
Fled from his wrath, and did themselues conuay
Eftsoones she causd him vp to be conuayd,
Themselues they forth conuayd, & passed forward right.
They did him set thereon, and forthwith them conuayd.
But Venus hers thence farre away conuayd,
Vnto their rest, and all the keyes conuayd
Till on his way they had him forth conuayd:
Or hard misfortune she was thence conuayd,
And them conuayd out at a Posterne dore.
Thence he him brought away, and vp conuayd
Or their owne guilt, they were away conuayd.
To be conuayed in, ere she would once retrate.
And time and place conuenient to areed,
In ydlesse, but as was conuenient,
For to auenge, in time conuenient,
Meaning so soone, as they conuenient may,
But all things did conueniently puruay:
Shall more conueniently in other place be ended.
And roote of ciuill conuersation.
For thus conuersing with this noble Knight;
She gan to stoupe, and her proud mind conuert
Her selfe eftsoones she gan conuert againe;
Conuerting, forth she beates the dustie path;
Conueyed quite away to liuing wight vnknowen.
That treasons could bewray, and foes conuince;
And Conway which out of his streame doth send
The maister Cooke was cald Concoction,
About the Caudron many Cookes accoyld,
For the coole shade him thither hastly got:
The valley did with coole shade ouercast,
To rest thy wearie person, in the shadow coole.
In the coole soile, after long thirstinesse,
And thee their mother call to coole their kindly rages.
So hasty heat soone cooled to subdew:
Ne ought the water cooled their whot bloud,
He feedes vpon the cooling shade, and bayes
Continually, and cooling breath inspyre.
And coosen vnto king Ambrosius:
Both coosen passions of distroubled spright,
Of his coosin Constantius without dread
My selfe will beare a part, coportion of your packe.
Shakt his long lockes, colourd like copper-wire,
Mine auncestry from famous Coradin,
Whose corage when the feend perceiu'd to shrinke,
In prime of youthly yeares, when corage hot
His corage more, that fro[m] his griping pawes
The flaming corage of that Faery knight,
To kindle heat of corage priuily:
Till crudled cold his corage gan assaile,
And he that breathlesse seemes, shal corage bold respire.
Their days mote be abridged through their corage stout.
Began to faint, and feele their corage cold.
Threatning to yoke them tow & tame their corage stout.
With curious Corbes and pendants grauen faire,
Abessa daughter of Corceca slow,
With wilfull cord, for wanting of her will;
Was much asham'd, that with an hempen cord
But Cordeill said she lou'd him, as behoou'd:
But without dowre the wise Cordelia
He to Cordelia him selfe addrest,
But that sweet Cordiall, which can restore
And costly Cordialles she did apply,
Fast bounden hand and foote with cords of wire,
They downe him hold, and fast with cords do bynde,
In gilden buskins of costly Cordwaine,
Buskins he wore of costliest cordwayne,
Corflambo chaseth Placidas,
Therefore Corflambo was he cald aright,
Coridon enuies him, yet he
But most of all the shepheard Coridon
Her fleecie flocke; but Coridon most helpe did giue.
Which seeing Coridon, who her likewise
And oft, when Coridon vnto her brought
Thereat frown'd Coridon, and his lip closely bit.
Tooke Coridon, and set him in his place,
For Coridon could daunce, and trimly trace.
Then Coridon woxe frollicke, that earst seemed dead.
There Coridon forth stepping openly,
Gaue it to Coridon, and said he wonne it well.
And euermore the shepheard Coridon,
Which Coridon first hearing, ran in hast
But Coridon for cowherdize reiect,
With them also was taken Coridon,
And Coridon, with many other moe,
But Coridon escaping craftily,
That Coridon it was, the silly shepherds hynd.
Tho Coridon he prayd, sith he well knew
Right well knew Coridon his owne late sheepe,
Whom Coridon him counseld to inuade
Were dead, right so as Coridon had taught:
But Coridon durst not with him consort,
He did them all to Coridon restore.
And did it put on Coridons in stead:
Corineus conquered, and cruelly did slay.
Corineus had that Prouince vtmost west,
The noble daughter of Corineus
Corineus, and Coulin of Debon old
Encloseth Corke with his deuided flood;
From a great Gyant, called Cormoraunt;
And Cormoyrants, with birds of rauenous race,
She found them both in darkesome corner pent;
And in another corner wide were strowne
Me leading, in a secret corner layd,
Then when he was defide, in coward corner ly.
Thou in dull corners doest thy selfe inclose,
And hid them selues in corners here and there;
He called Cornewaile, yet so called best:
In Cornewale, till that he through liues despeire
But later ages pride, like corn-fed steed,
And brother vnto Cador Cornish king,
The Cornish and the Deuonish confines;
And crowne your heades with heauenly coronall,
And by his side his Queene with coronall,
And on his head like to a Coronet
So louedst thou the faire Coronis deare:
His goodly corps on ragged cliffs yrent,
His corps was carried downe along the Lee,
Loe this dead corpse, that lies here vnderneath,
To clad his corpse with meete habiliments,
Whereas he meant his corrosiues to apply,
All those were lawlesse lustes, corrupt enuies,
She ment him to corrupt with goodly meede;
That now corrupt and curelesse they became.
That soone in him was left no one corrupted iot.
Corrupted by Paulinus, from her sweru'd:
Full many wounds in his corrupted flesh
Of present dayes, which are corrupted sore,
And with corruptfull brybes is to vntruth mis-trayned.
Inward corruption, and infected sin,
Fleshly corruption, nor mortall paine.
For now her wounds corruption gan to breed;
Corrupts the stomacke with gall vitious,
A streame of cole black bloud forth gushed fro[m]; her corse.
Then forth I went his woefull corse to find,
To haue attonce deuour'd her tender corse:
Drunke vp his life; his corse left on the strand.
For he was strong, and of so mightie corse,
His dronken corse he scarse vpholden can,
And brought the heauie corse with easie pace
For that Hippolytus rent corse he did redresse.
Then vp he tooke the slombred sencelesse corse,
His pined corse, him scarse to light could beare,
A drearie corse, whose life away did pas,
His daintie corse, proud humors to abate,
That nought mote perce, ne might his corse be harmd
The senselesse corse appointed for the graue.
To spoile her daintie corse so faire and sheene,
The dead corse of an armed knight was spred,
And fowly battered his comely corse,
Keeping that slombred corse to him assynd;
And deadly hew, an armed corse did lye,
And all decrepit in his feeble corse,
Or his dead corse should fall vpon the flore;
But his dead corse vpon the flore fell nathemore.
The lumpish corse vnto the senselesse grownd;
And hauing scruzd out of his carrion corse
Whiles they the corse into her wagon reare,
In loathly wise like to a carion corse,
